<table class="drug-table data-table table table-condensed table-bordered"><tbody><tr id="identification"><th class="divider" colspan="2">Identification</th></tr><tr><th>Name</th><td><strong>Teicoplanin</strong></td></tr><tr><th>Accession Number</th><td><strong>DB06149</strong></td></tr><tr><th>Type</th><td>biotech</td></tr><tr><th>Groups</th><td>approved</td></tr><tr><th>Description</th><td><p>Teicoplanin is a glycopeptide antibiotic. It is a mixture of several compounds, five major (named teicoplanin A2-1 through A2-5) and four minor (named teicoplanin RS-1 through RS-4). All teicoplanins share a same glycopeptide core, termed teicoplanin A3-1, a fused ring structure to which two carbohydrates (mannose and N-acetylglucosamine) are attached. The major and minor components also contain a third carbohydrate moiety, &#946;-D-glucosamine, and differ only by the length and conformation of a side chain attached to it. [Wikipedia]</p></td></tr><tr><th>Protein structure</th><td><img alt="No structure small" src="/assets/no_structure_small-e8790a148b09ecc5ad9f5b4926a538e7.png"></td></tr><tr><th>Protein chemical formula</th><td>C<sub>88</sub>H<sub>97</sub>Cl<sub>2</sub>N<sub>9</sub>O<sub>33</sub></td></tr><tr><th>Protein average weight</th><td>1879.6580</td></tr><tr><th>Sequences</th><td></td></tr><tr><th>Synonyms</th><td class="data-table-container"><table class="table table-condensed table-striped datatable" id="synonyms"><thead><th>Synonym</th><th>Language</th><th>Code</th></thead><tbody><tr><td>TEIC</td><td><span class="wishart wishart-not-available">Not Available</span></td><td><span class="wishart wishart-not-available">Not Available</span></td></tr><tr><td>Teichomycin</td><td><span class="wishart wishart-not-available">Not Available</span></td><td><span class="wishart wishart-not-available">Not Available</span></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><th>Salts</th><td><span class="wishart wishart-not-available">Not Available</span></td></tr><tr><th>Brand names</th><td c